        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> Here's a slight caveat to the argument played out here about chaincasting...</P><P>According to VI, there's a cap on the number of pets that will actually do damage to a single mob during a fight.  Any additional pets over a total of four will swing at thin air.  So while additional pets are good for backup - to fill in when the others go down - no more than four will be actually having an effect at a given time.</P><P>Soooo... if you're on a raid with a bunch of other mages and necros, y'all might want to balance your strategies.</P><P>I'm not saying this is a killer to chaincasting.  It's definitely more of an attractive strategy now.  I am saying that wet dreams of taking on major mobs with hoards of pets are probably just that.</P><P>Here's what I would do in a raid situation where pets were allowed:  Set up a cycle of chain casting among 5 mages/necros where you always have 5 up at a given time (so that when one goes down, there is immediately one to fill the void).  I suppose you could add to the pool of casters depending on how fast the pets were getting eaten up.</P><P>Just some thoughts :)</P><P></P><P>- Takilth Shadowpath (aka Necrotart)<BR>  Iksar necromancer of the 57th shedding<BR>  proud member of Phoenix Elite<BR>  Prexus<BR></font></td>
